alt="marieandmiles_kirkwood"/></a></div><div class="hz-question__info"><div class="hz-question__title-container"><h1 class="hz-question__title header-2" itemProp="headline">Downdraft cooktop cabinet advice</h1></div><div class="hz-question__detail text-m text-dt-s"><div itemProp="author" itemType="http://schema.org/Person" itemscope=""><a href="https://www.houzz.com/user/marieandmiles-kirkwood" class="hz-username text-bold" data-type="profile" data-id="marieandmiles_kirkwood" itemProp="url"><span itemProp="name">Marie and Miles Kirkwood</span></a></div><span class="hz-question__date"><div class="hz-question__date--created"><meta itemProp="dateCreated" content="2025-06-03T18:37:54.000Z"/><span><span>10 days ago</span></span></div><div class="hz-question__date--modified"><meta itemProp="dateModified" content="2025-06-05T01:22:58.000Z"/>last modified: <span><span>9 days ago</span></span></div></span></div></div></div><div class="message-body new-message-body text-l" itemProp="text"><p>I need help with the INSIDE of a cabinet.  We bought an Elica induction cooktop with downdraft that we are installing in our new IKEA kitchen.  The cooktop is 32" and the cabinet is 36" so plenty of space on the top and inside the cabinet.  However, the 6" downdraft venting goes right through the middle of the cabinet.</p>
<p>I need some suggestions before the cooktop is installed on how to finish the inside so that I can have some usable storage under the cooktop.  I need some advice BEFORE the cooktop is installed in case I need to feed some shelves through the ducting.  I have 2 IKEA shelves for this cabinet that are still in plastic, I'm holding on to until we figure this out.</p>
<p>NOTE: The pics are from different stages of the renovation - inside cabinet from before the counter went on and the cooktop for depth 8 1/2" and then 2 other pics to explain the backsplash and windows seen behind.</p>
<p>There is approximately 13" of space on either side of the venting.</p>
<p>Any suggestions would be appreciated.<br /></p><div class="message-component message-body__image" key="b932b341083f4101"><img class="img-responsive cursor-magnify" data-type="15" data-id="b932b341083f4101" data-imgid="b932b341083f4101" data-cm="5873" data-compid="body_content_img" src="https://st.hzcdn.com/fimgs/b932b341083f4101_5873-w500-h666-b0-p0--.jpg" width="500" height="666" alt loading="eager" /></div><p></p>
<p><br /><br /></p><div class="message-component message-body__image" key="006299c40840f16f"><img class="img-responsive cursor-magnify" data-type="15" data-id="006299c40840f16f" data-imgid="006299c40840f16f" data-cm="6576" data-compid="body_content_img" src="https://st.hzcdn.com/fimgs/006299c40840f16f_6576-w500-h666-b0-p0--.jpg" width="500" height="666" alt loading="eager" /></div><p></p>
<p><br /></p><div class="message-component message-body__image" key="40f28d160840f170"><img class="img-responsive cursor-magnify" data-type="15" data-id="40f28d160840f170" data-imgid="40f28d160840f170" data-cm="6576" data-compid="body_content_img" src="https://st.hzcdn.com/fimgs/40f28d160840f170_6576-w500-h666-b0-p0--.jpg" width="500" height="666" alt loading="eager" /></div><p></p>
<p><br /><br /></p><div class="message-component message-body__image" key="3d62bd5f0840f170"><img class="img-responsive cursor-magnify" data-type="15" data-id="3d62bd5f0840f170" data-imgid="3d62bd5f0840f170" data-cm="6577" data-compid="body_content_img" src="https://st.hzcdn.com/fimgs/3d62bd5f0840f170_6577-w500-h666-b0-p0--.jpg" width="500" height="666" alt loading="eager" /></div><p></p>
<p><br /></p><div class="message-component message-body__image" key="db329a500840f171"><img class="img-responsive cursor-magnify" data-type="15" data-id="db329a500840f171" data-imgid="db329a500840f171" data-cm="6578" data-compid="body_content_img" src="https://st.hzcdn.com/fimgs/db329a500840f171_6578-w500-h666-b0-p0--.jpg" width="500" height="666" alt loading="eager" /></div><p></p>
<p>Thanks!</p>
</div><div class="hz-question__social" data-container="Discussion Actions"><div class="hz-user-action-bar hz-user-actions hz-track-me"><button class="btn btn-default  hz-user-action-button class="icon-font icon-paper_plane  hz-user-action-button__icon" aria-hidden="true"></span><span class=" btn__label ">Email</span></button><button class="btn btn-default  hz-user-action-button aria-hidden="true"></span><span class=" btn__label ">Save</span></button><button class="btn btn-default  hz-user-action-button hz-user-action-bar__btn hz-user-action-bar__btn--comment" scopeid="viewQuestion" data-component="Comment" anchortext="Comment" data-entity-id="6497786" data-entity-type="5" type="button"><span class="icon-font icon-sb_solid  hz-user-action-button__icon" class="hz-comments__featured-comment"><div class="hz-comments__featured-comment-title"><div class="hz-comments__title header-4">Featured Answer</div><span class="icon-font icon-circle_question " aria-hidden="true"></span></div><li class="comment-list__item  comment-list__best-comment-background" id="29509464"><div class="comment-list__item-container  comment-list__best-comment-container" itemProp="comment" itemType="https://schema.org/Comment" itemscope=""><div class="comment-list__item-avatar pull-left mrm"><a class="user-avatar-link" href="https://www.houzz.com/user/jwvideo"><img class="comment-list__item-avatar-img hz-user-image" width="40" height="40" src="//www.houzz.com/res/29162442/pic/user_0.png?v=29162442" alt=""/></a></div><div class="comment-list__item-content"><div itemProp="author" itemType="https://schema.org/Person" itemscope=""><h6 class="comment-list__item-username text-m text-bold"><a href="https://www.houzz.com/user/jwvideo" itemProp="url"><span itemProp="name">jwvideo</span></a></h6></div><div class="comment-list__item-time"><div class="comment-list__item-time--created text-xs text-muted"><span><span>9 days ago</span></span><meta itemProp="dateCreated" content="2025-06-04T17:03:33.000Z"/></div><div class="comment-list__item-time--modified text-xs text-muted">last modified: <span><span>8 days ago</span></span><meta itemProp="dateModified" content="2025-06-05T18:23:09.000Z"/></div></div><div role="button" tabindex="0" class="hz-peekable__container"><div class="hz-peekable__mask"><div class="slide-toggle  slide-toggle--collapsed" style="max-height:140px"><div class="message-body new-message-body text-l" itemProp="text"><p>FWIW, what I'm seeing in the photo is that the windows and door are on a different wall and not directly above the cooktop and backsplash. They appear to me to be in a back wall, or maybe the one that has the upper cabinets and is at right angles to the counter with the cooktop.  Apparently, whoever is cooking will be able see over the backsplash down into some lowered living space  beyond, Maybe a family room or dining space in what used to be called a sunken or split-level space?</p>
<p>Anyway, if  you can go down to where the "undercarriage" housing is only about the width of the six inch wide venting structure, then notching a shelf around it would be the way to go , as recommened above. </p>
<p>However, a quick (and probably inadequate) search turned up an Elica  <a href="https://damsrv.elica.com/doc/Americas/SPEC_SHEETS/elica_ss_NTFlux_2024_ENF430BL_ENF436BL.pdf" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" class="link-external colorLink">installation instruction pdf</a> and some YouTube installation videos which show Elica cooktops with a rather large 11" inch deep "undercarriage"  that extends across much more of the bottom of the unit than the vent box seen in the top photo, above. That seems to leave maybe only 4 inches of space or so to either side of the undercarriage in a 36" wide base cabinet.  If that is the case, then it doesn't seem worth trying to notch a shelf around it.</p>
<p>And if that is the case with the your Elica s unit, it would leave only about 17 or 18 inches of vertical space below it for shelving in that IKEA cabinet.   For pots and pan storage, maybe use just one of the IKEA shelves, with shallow pans like skillets on the shelf and taller pots and pans below?  Or add the second shelf for spaces to stack other relatively shallow items like sheet pans, cake pans, cookie sheets, etc?  </p>

itemType="https://schema.org/Person" itemscope=""><h6 class="comment-list__item-username text-m text-bold"><a href="https://www.houzz.com/professionals/general-contractors/minardi-pfvwus-pf~1833970505" itemProp="url"><span itemProp="name">Minardi</span></a></h6></div><div class="comment-list__item-time"><div class="comment-list__item-time--created text-xs text-muted"><span><span>10 days ago</span></span><meta itemProp="dateCreated" content="2025-06-03T21:01:59.000Z"/></div><div class="comment-list__item-time--modified text-xs text-muted">last modified: <span><span>10 days ago</span></span><meta itemProp="dateModified" content="2025-06-03T21:02:37.000Z"/></div></div><div class="message-body new-message-body text-l" itemProp="text"><p>If you want a useable cabinet below a cooktop then you don't put in a useless downdraft.  You do overhead venting, and then do pot and pan drawers below.  Plus, you need to pull that entire run 6" off the wall, to be safe against what should be safety glass. </p>

class="comment-list__item-username text-m text-bold"><a href="https://www.houzz.com/user/dan1888" itemProp="url"><span itemProp="name">dan1888</span></a></h6></div><div class="comment-list__item-time"><div class="comment-list__item-time--created text-xs text-muted"><span><span>10 days ago</span></span><meta itemProp="dateCreated" content="2025-06-03T21:22:00.000Z"/></div></div><div class="message-body new-message-body text-l" itemProp="text"><p>I'd treat the cabinet like a bathroom cabinet below a sink. You notch and or box the shelve or better yet drawers to close around the vent duct. For shelves you may need a ledger type 1  x 2 screwed through the back material into the 1 x 2 to rest the shelf on on either side of the duct cutout.</p>
</div></div><div class="comment-list__item-footer" data-container="Comment Actions" itemProp="interactionStatistic" itemType="https://schema.org/InteractionCounter" itemscope=""><meta itemProp="interactionType" content="https://schema.org/LikeAction"/><meta itemProp="userInteractionCount" content="1"/><ul class="comment-list__item-actions text-xxs text-muted mb0 mrl"><li class="comment-list__item-action comment-list__item-action--like"><button class="comment-list__item-action-btn btn btn-link pl0 pr0"><span class="icon-font icon-thumb_solid comment-list__item-action-btn-icon " aria-hidden="true" data-compid="comment_like" data-component="Like"></span><span class="comment-list__item-action-btn-label text-bold text-xs mls" aria-hidden="true" ata-component="Like" data-compid="comment_show_like">Like | 1</span></button></li><li class="comment-list__item-action comment-list__item-action--save mlm"><button class="comment-list__item-action-btn btn btn-link pl0 pr0" data-component="Save" data-compid="comment_save"><span class="icon-font icon-heart_outline comment-list__item-action-btn-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span><span class="comment-list__item-action-btn-label text-bold text-xs mls">Save</span></button></li></ul></div><div class="comment-list__item-best-comment"></div></div></li><li class="comment-list__item comment-list__injectable"><div class="hz-comments__inline-question"><h2 class="header-6">Related Professionals</h2><a href="https://www.houzz.com/professionals/kitchen-and-bath/st-louis-mo-us-probr0-bo~t_11790~r_4407066">St. Louis Kitchen &amp; Yes the duct will be visible.  Spray it black or white or something.  </p>
<p><br />The ledger dan1888 describes is to support the back of the shelf which is weakened by the cut.  If the cabinets have already been fastened down, you can drill holes in the 1x2 and cabinet back and use nuts and bolts, since you can still get your hand down between the studs.   Failing that, you can screw the 1x2 to the rear bottom edge of the self itself to strengthen it, and don't load the shelf up with stacks of your heaviest cast iron cookware.  </p>
</div></div><div class="comment-list__item-footer" data-container="Comment Actions" itemProp="interactionStatistic" itemType="https://schema.org/InteractionCounter" itemscope=""><meta </div></div><div class="comment-list__item-footer" data-container="Comment Actions" itemProp="interactionStatistic" itemType="https://schema.org/InteractionCounter" itemscope=""><meta itemProp="interactionType" content="https://schema.org/LikeAction"/><meta itemProp="userInteractionCount" content="2"/><ul class="comment-list__item-actions text-xxs text-muted mb0 mrl"><li class="comment-list__item-action comment-list__item-action--like"><button class="comment-list__item-action-btn btn btn-link pl0 pr0"><span class="icon-font icon-thumb_solid aria-hidden="true" ata-component="Like" data-compid="comment_show_like">Like | 2</span></button></li><li class="comment-list__item-action comment-list__item-action--save mlm"><button class="comment-list__item-action-btn btn btn-link pl0 pr0" data-component="Save" data-compid="comment_save"><span class="icon-font icon-heart_outline comment-list__item-action-btn-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span><span class="comment-list__item-action-btn-label text-bold text-xs mls">Save</span></button></li></ul></div><div class="comment-list__item-best-comment"></div></div></li><li class="comment-list__item  " id="29509904"><div class="comment-list__item-container  comment-list__best-comment-container" itemProp="comment" itemType="https://schema.org/Comment" itemscope=""><div class="comment-list__item-avatar pull-left mrm"><a class="user-avatar-link" href="https://www.houzz.com/user/marieandmiles-kirkwood"><img class="comment-list__item-avatar-img hz-user-image" width="40" height="40" src="//www.houzz.com/res/29162442/pic/user_0.png?v=29162442" alt=""/></a></div><div class="comment-list__item-content"><div itemProp="author" itemType="https://schema.org/Person" itemscope=""><h6 class="comment-list__item-username text-m text-bold"><a href="https://www.houzz.com/user/marieandmiles-kirkwood" itemProp="url"><span itemProp="name">Marie and Miles Kirkwood</span></a><div class="comment-list__item-author-tag text-xxs text-muted">Original Author</div></h6></div><div class="comment-list__item-time"><div class="comment-list__item-time--created text-xs text-muted"><span><span>9 days ago</span></span><meta itemProp="dateCreated" content="2025-06-05T01:34:08.000Z"/></div></div><div class="message-body new-message-body text-l" itemProp="text"><p>Thanks so much for all of the responses so far.  We can't add overhead venting because the kitchen overlooks the family room (2 steps below). </p>
<p>I've added some more photos to explain the windows and why we have that short backsplash. The cooktop is only 8 1/2" deep. I like the idea of cutting out the middle and making a horseshoe, but I'm not sure it would be sturdy enough to hold anything and might crack or bend over time so adding a support across the back would be needed so it doesn't warp.</p>
<p>I've looked at some narrow pullout shelves (NOT Shelf Genie $$$$) but I'm not sure how useful they'd be for the cost - unless I use the storage below the cooktop for cooking utensils or oils/seasoning?</p>
<p>I really like the idea of cutting a 7" hole in the middle leaving the sides and front and back for support of a shelf but I'd still be tempted to add a support brace across the back.</p>
<p>And you're right JWVIDEO I'd only be able to fit 1 shelf in here.  I'm saving the 2nd one as an option to cut a better/tighter opening and cover up the irregularly shaped opening my contractor made.</p>
<p>If anyone else has any other suggestions, I'd appreciate it!</p>

<span><span>9 days ago</span></span><meta itemProp="dateModified" content="2025-06-05T14:14:13.000Z"/></div></div><div class="message-body new-message-body text-l" itemProp="text"><p>We have an induction cooktop with downdraft in an island.  Overhead exhaust is not possible with a bedroom directly above. While the shape is a little different, it mostly affected the rear storage area.  The upper storage shelf is cut in a squared U-shape to match the initial downdraft housing.. *see photo*  We had a similar shelf installed to maximize storage with cutout around it, just like in our bathroom vanity for the drainpipe to get a middle shelf for storage.  </p><div class="message-component message-body__image" key="ff32254c0841a50c"><img class="img-responsive cursor-magnify" data-type="15" data-id="ff32254c0841a50c" data-imgid="ff32254c0841a50c" data-cm="2557" data-compid="body_content_img" src="https://st.hzcdn.com/fimgs/ff32254c0841a50c_2557-w240-h194-b0-p0--.jpg" width="240" height="194" alt loading="eager" /></div><p></p>

itemProp="dateCreated" content="2025-06-06T00:27:57.000Z"/></div></div><div class="message-body new-message-body text-l" itemProp="text"><p>@Marie &amp; Miles Kirkwood -- the  understructure on your Elica unit may extend only 8½" below the cooktop but installation instructions for induction cooktops may specify additional clearance and air-space. Maybe, for example, to assure properly cooling the internals.  Best check your unit's install instructions or check with Elica tech or customer support to find out before trying to fit shelving around or close to it. </p>

Has anyone tried this yet? My wife and I haven't tried a lot of induction cooktops, but we've tried multiple in apartments we've rented in Paris, and the controls are all TERRIBLE (touch panels not responsive). The best controls are on our $99 portable induction hobs we use for hot pot.\nIts compelling features are:\n1. Physical knobs. There's nothing more intuitive than a knob. I realize for young folk that's not true, but there's something to be said for physical controls. Also knobs are magnetic and removable for cleaning.\n2. Temperature control. Set the temp, and the induction increases and decreases wattage as needed to reach and maintain set temp.\n3. 10 kW available power. 40 seconds to boil 1L of water. Massive power, but drops power use as soon as it reaches 212 F or whatever temp, unlike others which start out lower (3.7 kW usually) but keep using 3.7 kW even when you need way less power to maintain temp.\n3. Cook during a power outage. It contains a 3 kWh lithium battery, which is how it achieves 10 kW of power with 120 or 240V w/o tripping your breaker.\n4. Home battery backup. They're planning on producing more appliances with batteries so you can have backup power for your home. I live in SDG&amp;E territory, the most expensive power in the USA, and I would love to run my power off this battery during peak hours of 4-9 pm.\nI'm trying to talk my wife into trying this + ovens instead of a range. She's a die-hard gas cooking fan and fan of ranges, and she's the boss. Happy wife, happy life!","numberOfAnswers":6,"seoHint":{"paths":{"ViewDiscussion":{"command":"discussions","titleSlug":"has-anyone-tried-impulse-labs-30-induction-cooktop","seoPageType":"dsvw","indexing":true}}}},{"id":6498271,"title":"Jenn Air Column Refrigerator  and Freezer","body":"Just designing a kitchen renovation and am considering the Jennair column fridge and freezer appliances.
